<component type="desktop-application">
    <id>menu.kando.Kando</id>

    <name>Kando</name>
    <summary>Do things with utmost efficiency</summary>

    <metadata_license>CC0-1.0</metadata_license>
    <project_license>MIT</project_license>

    <supports>
        <control>pointing</control>
        <control>keyboard</control>
        <control>touch</control>
        <control>gamepad</control>
        <control>tablet</control>
    </supports>

    <description>
        <p>
            Kando is a cross-platform pie menu for your desktop. It offers an unconventional, fast,
            highly efficient, and fun way of interacting with your computer! You can use Kando to
            launch applications, simulate keyboard shortcuts, open files, and much more.
        </p>
        <p>
            Kando is designed to be used with üñ±Ô∏è mouse, üñäÔ∏è stylus, üëÜ touch, or üéÆ controller input.
            If you have both hands at your keyboard most of the time, Kando is maybe not the right
            tool for you.
        </p>
        <p>
            If you are using Kando on Wayland, some additional setup may be required. For instance,
            on GNOME you will need to install the Kando Integration extension. You can read more on
            https://kando.menu/installation-on-linux/. Kando will also tell you this when you start
            it for the first time.
        </p>
    </description>

